ation","justification":"The edit distance algorithm itself is Unit-testable (pure function, deterministic). But the full behavior requires *persistent* storage of the metric. Real failures appear in the storage layer: serialization errors, wrong format, metric never actually written, or retrieval failing later. Mocking storage would hide these. The behavior requires both correct computation (Unit) and correct persistence (Integration).","test_description":"With both primary and fallback translations available, call the quality tracking component. Verify edit distance is computed correctly (spot-check against known examples like 'cat' vs 'bat' = 1, 'kitten' vs 'sitting' = 3). Verify the metric is stored to persistent storage (database, log file, etc.) and can be retrieved in a later query or inspection.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When both primary and fallback translators are available, the service returns the primary translation to the caller synchronously and logs the quality comparison metrics in the background asynchronously without blocking.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is the full happy-path behavior, and it critically depends on the real NMT API call. The service must integrate the live API output with the quality tracking and fallback system. Real failures include: API call not placed correctly, API response not handled in the integration chain, or quality metrics computed on artificial (mocked) data instead of real divergence between live primary and fallback outputs. The behavior is only meaningful if tested with the real, non-deterministic API output. Additionally, logging must occur in the background without blocking the caller—a failure here requires end-to-end system interaction, not just isolated logic.","test_description":"Call the service with source text using the real NMT API and real SQLite database.